ItemDescription.Value: The wine made from the Mon spring water at the foot of Huagai Mountain has a mellow and sweet taste and a long aftertaste.
The sake is made from a waterfall spring in Hanju and has a sweet, refreshing taste.
A kind of wine brewed with glutinous rice, which is common in Qingzhou and Ruzhou, has a sweet taste, but unfortunately, it is not easy to preserve and precipitation will occur over time.
The rice wine is soft and richly flavored with layers of glutinous rice, making you feel like you are in the fairyland of Penglai with just one sip.
The wine is made from a small stream in Puzhou with clear and fresh water, and it is named "Hosho Wine" because of the fine waves on the surface of the water when it is taken.

The wine can only be made in the winter months, with castrated ram meat mixed with fermented glutinous rice steamed, cooled and then moved into the wine quill, sealed in the altar. The white sheep wine has a unique mellow feeling in the mouth, which must be due to the sheep fat.
The peach from Qingzhou is used as the raw material to make the fruity, sweet and fragrant Hundred Peach Wine.

The white wine made from green plums is called Bixiang. Because plum blossoms have always represented noble temperament, they were loved by dignitaries and noblemen, and green plums are a rare species of plum blossoms. This wine is refreshing in the mouth and has a faint fragrance of plum blossoms on the nose.
A fruit wine brewed from pomegranates is called Chaohya wine because of its orange and red color, brilliant like a sunset. This wine is sweet and sour and is very suitable for summer drinking.
There are 72 large and small springs in Qi Zhou. Near Spring Wine is made from one of these springs.
Lin fat itself means jade liquid and jelly, so it is clear that this wine is of high quality and worth a try.
The sake is made from the spring water from the White Jade Spring on the North Road of Jinghu. Spicy and sweet, it is a must try for those who like strong liquor.
Bilantang is a private courtyard in Huzhou, where a kind of homemade wine is made, which is not well known, but later became famous due to a poem by calligrapher Chen Yaozuo.
A kind of official wine, famous for Lu You's poem.
A wine that you will often see on Liangzhe Road and is loved by the general public. This wine is not high in degree and has a refreshing taste.
Brewed from grain produced in Lanxi, the sake is sold every spring and has a strong aroma of sorghum.
The local wine of Gyeongju is clear and transparent, elegant and delicate, soft in the mouth, refreshing and sweet, and a wine not to be missed.
The wine is made from aged Fen wine, and refined with precious herbs such as light bamboo leaves, Chen Pi, sandalwood, and grit. It is golden in color, mellow in aroma, soft and refreshing in taste.
The wine made from the Zijin Spring in Zhenjiang has a sweet taste and fragrant aroma.
Heavenly Book Pavilion storyteller homemade wine, fragrant for miles, the secret recipe no one knows. There is no sale on the market, you can only go to the Heavenly Book Pavilion to try your luck.

A famous Shaanxi wine. It is made from high quality red sorghum, drawn from the sweet and clean Gaoxia spring water, fermented in a mud cellar, and slowly distilled, making it rich and harmonious, full and mellow.
The wine came from the Excitement Depot and was exclusively for the border guards to drink, but later became famous because it was loved by Lu You.
The wine was inadvertently tasted by Lu You when he was on his way to Suzhou, and later he wrote a poem to make it famous. This wine is fresh and elegant, and has the same atmosphere as Suzhou.

It is said to be made by the Wu family of Empress Wu of King Gao. The wine has a bright amber color, deep red with a slight orange tinge, and a faint floral aroma on the nose. The taste is warm and mellow, sweet and sour, with a long and refreshing aftertaste.

During the Eastern Jin Dynasty, Zhenjiang, which was located in a key area of the Yangtze River, became a major military town, and the army formed was called the "Northern Government Army". This wine was used as a reward for the army at that time, and the recipe has been used to this day.

The bottle is popular because of its resemblance to a gourd and its resonance to the sound "Fu Lu".
Inspired by the evolution of the water purification bottle in the monastery, it is an unusual vessel for serving wine.
It is also known as the "warp vase". It is popular because of its beautiful shape.
The body is covered with red glaze, the glaze is moist and thick, and the foot is large, with a wide circle of exposed tire reed, on which a fine swirling pattern is revealed.
The neck is thin, the abdomen is shaped like a dangling gall, and the footrim is slightly flared. The whole is covered with a warm, jade-like azure glaze and covered with uniform openings.
The abdomen is concave on all sides and is melon-ribbed. The footrim is flared. The whole body is covered with white glaze, and the glaze is lustrous.
The shape of the vessel is beautiful, the glaze is mottled like partridge hair color, the flow is exquisite, and it is wonderfully interesting.
This is a table marble for presenting wine. Pure white glaze, although extremely simple, but the mapping of the eerie extremely plain light.
The tire color is white and the texture is delicate. The base glaze has a shadow green, and the jade is engraved with a peony decoration, which is a relatively rare wine vessel.

It is said that the person who developed this cup was inspired by the ancient zither song "Wind and Thunder". The cup is light and thin like the wind, and its shape is angular and resembles thunder, making it a distinctive and eye-catching wine cup.
The blue-green color produced by high-temperature obsidian resembles the feathers of a peacock. Because the color of obsidian is not controllable, each peacock cup is unique.

A wine cup made in the shape of a longevity flower, also known as a fairy flower cup. The color is clear and the green glaze is mostly used. The cups were popular among the dignitaries because they meant longevity and immortality, so they were expensive.
Made of translucent white jade, the cups were produced in small quantities and were loved by the literati because of their elegant and icy shape.

It is said to have been inspired by the poet Wang Han's poem "Lyrics from Liangzhou", in which he wrote "Grapes and Wine in the Night". The wine mentioned in the poem is called Yulu wine, and the glass gives off a dazzling light under the moonlight.
A valuable drinking vessel made of green jade. When the wine is placed in the cup and placed under the moonlight, the cup will shine.

The wine marquee is glazed in black, with a hollowed-out leaf made of pure silver embedded in the bottom of the marquee. When the wine is poured, the silver leaf reflects the silver light, forming a sharp contrast with the black body.
